# Project: YorùbáOCR Research

## What this project is
A benchmark dataset + fine-tuning study for Yorùbá OCR submitted to
Deep Learning Indaba 2026 (IJCAI volume). The researcher built a custom
annotation platform (yoruba-ocr.vercel.app) and exported data in
PaddleOCR VL-1.5 format.

## Verified dataset facts (do not invent alternatives)
- Source: Yorùbá di Wúrà Book Series (printed books, 2021)
- Language: Standard Yorùbá, corrected=yes for all entries
- Format: line crops (PNG) + tab-separated label files (PaddleOCR format)
  - Each label line: images/{split}/hash_lineNNNN.png<TAB>ground_truth_text
- 25+ independent annotation export batches in data/raw/
- Approximate totals across all exports: ~3,481 train / ~350 val / ~539 test
  (exact unique counts produced after running 01_consolidate_data.py)
- Character dictionary: 102 chars including combining diacritics (U+0300, U+0301, U+0323)
  and precomposed Yorùbá characters (ẹ, ọ, ṣ, and all tonal variants)
- Metadata columns: image, text, source, year, dialect, corrected, parent_image, line_index
- Consolidated data lives in data/processed/ after running 01_consolidate_data.py

## Pipeline scripts (in execution order)
1. scripts/01_consolidate_data.py  — merge exports, deduplicate, copy to data/processed/
2. scripts/02_analyze_dataset.py   — EDA: char/diacritic distribution, text length stats
3. scripts/03_generate_config.py   — download pretrained weights + write fine-tune YAML
4. scripts/04_train_paddleocr.py   — run PaddleOCR fine-tuning (needs PaddleOCR repo)
5. scripts/05_evaluate.py          — CER/WER/DER evaluation for any model
6. scripts/06_baseline_pretrained.py — English pretrained model baseline

## Models being compared
1. PaddleOCR PP-OCRv4 (English pretrained — baseline, no fine-tuning)
2. PaddleOCR PP-OCRv4 (fine-tuned on Yorùbá dataset)
3. Tesseract (baseline — add later)
4. Mistral OCR (zero-shot — add later)
5. Qwen 2.5 VL (zero-shot multimodal — add later)

## Metrics
- CER — Character Error Rate (NFC-normalised edit distance / gt char count)
- WER — Word Error Rate (NFC-normalised word-level edit distance / gt word count)
- DER — Diacritic Error Rate (novel contribution):
    pred_diacs = [c for c in NFD(pred) if unicodedata.combining(c)]
    gt_diacs   = [c for c in NFD(gt)   if unicodedata.combining(c)]
    DER = edit_distance(pred_diacs, gt_diacs) / len(gt_diacs)
  Measures tone mark and subdot fidelity specifically — the key failure mode
  of English pretrained models on Yorùbá text.

## All results must be traceable
- Every number in the paper must map to an entry in results/tables/metrics.csv
- Per-sample JSONL logs are written alongside every eval run
- Never write a metric value in prose that is not in results/tables/

## Terminology: always use these exact forms
- Yorùbá (with diacritics, never "Yoruba")
- diacritic minimal pairs (not "similar characters")
- toneme, tonograph, combining diacritic
- low-resource (hyphenated when modifier)
- fine-tuning (hyphenated)
- CER, WER, DER (always capitalised)

